{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d3f6dd72-77bd-4678-b471-091c9f66c754","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_016dYXMoTLhtAUhHeMhmax7q","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Providing K8s crash dump config"},"type":"function"}],"interactionId":"1b8e1296-1461-4468-8271-7fd827fc782a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` installed at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me provide the configuration needed.\n\nFor .NET NativeAOT crash dump collection, the key environment variables are:\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` - enables automatic crash dump generation\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` - sets the dump type (1=Normal, 2=WithHeap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` - controls where the dump files are written\n- `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` - enables diagnostics output during dump creation\n- `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` - points to the custom createdump location at `/opt/tools/createdump`\n\nI need to reconsider this for NativeAOT though—since it doesn't use the CoreCLR runtime, the standard CLR dump mechanisms might not apply the same way.\n\nActually, starting with .NET 8, NativeAOT does support crash dumps using the same environment variables, but the createdump tool path still needs to be explicitly set since NativeAOT apps don't have access to the runtime's default tool directory. For Kubernetes, I'll need to account for a volume to store the dumps, set the environment variables on the container, and potentially enable process namespace sharing if using sidecars. Let me put together a pod spec example.","outputTokens":534,"requestId":"DA04:FFF68:230E242:26C4B06:6A03D868"},"id":"735743ea-c42e-4a8b-8a22-fd82f166062e","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:48:36.189Z","parentId":"f1b8bb45-82bf-458d-8d61-fb86870b252e"}
